<!DOCTYPE en-note SYSTEM "http://xml.evernote.com/pub/enml2.dtd">
<en-note><div>Cron</div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">Minute   Hour DayOfMonth   Month   DayOfWeek       ---&gt; Program to execute</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">Minute : 0 --&gt; 59</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">'*' - means every minute</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">'00' - the top of hour ( depend on  the HOUR set)</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">                For instance, if HOUR set 16 (4 PM) it will be 16:00</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">'20' - 20th minute of an hour. (i.e. 10:20 or 14:20)</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">'*/10' - means every 10 minutes ( i.e. 00, 10, 20,30, 40, 50)</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">HOUR : 0 --&gt; 23</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">'*' - every hour</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">'11,16' - means at 11 AM and 4 PM  </span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">        '11-16' - range from 11 AM to 4 PM</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">DOB ( Day Of Month): 1--&gt; 31</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">        Note: Add '0' front of 1-9 ( i.e. 01, 02, 03.., 09)</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">        '*'  - means everyday</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">MONTH : 1 --&gt; 12</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">         01, 02, 03, …,12</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">        '*' - means every month</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">DOW ( Day of Week ): 0 --&gt; 6</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">        '0' - Sunday, '1' - Monday, … '5' - Friday'  and '6' - Saturday</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">        '*' - means every day of a week </span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">--------------------------------------- PATH ------------------------------------</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">Usually you have to specify the absolute path to your executable file.</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">To schedule my &quot;</span><a style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;" href="http://backup.sh">backup.sh</a><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">&quot; program which is located in '/home/khasanov/bin' ,</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">I have tell the crone the absolute path: /home/khasanov/bin/backup.sh.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">However, I can set the PATH environment to include that path:</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">PATH=${PATH}/home/khasanov/bin</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"># Common used PATH's</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">SHELL</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">/bin/sh</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92; font-weight: bold;">The cron knows nothing about the ${…} substitution. So, don't do these:</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92; font-weight: bold;">PATH</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92;">=${</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92; font-weight: bold;">PATH</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92;">}:/sbin:/usr/sbin:/usr/local/sbin</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92; font-weight: bold;">PATH</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92;">=${</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92; font-weight: bold;">PATH</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92;">}:/bin:/usr/bin:/usr/local/bin</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">PATH</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #941100;">/sbin:/bin:/usr/bin:/usr/local/bin</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">   </span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">-------------------------------------- Crontab ----------------------------------</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"># To View the Crontab Entries:</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=&gt; </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">crontab</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> -</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #941100;">l  </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">    ( small &quot;L&quot;)</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"># To Edit the Crontab</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=&gt;</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;"> crontab</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> -</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #941100;">e</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"># To Edit the Crontab as a root:</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=&gt;</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;"> su -</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92;">root</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=&gt;</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;"> crontab</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> -</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #941100;">e</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"># To Edit other </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #011993;">user</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">'s crontab entries:</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=&gt; </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">su -</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #ff2f92;">root </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">  (login as a root first)</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=&gt; </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">crontab</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> -</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #941100;">u</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #0433ff;">khasanov</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> -</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; color: #941100;">e </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">    ( to edit Karshi's crontab)</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"># Installing crontab form a file:</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">1.</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">Create a crontab file ( means with the cron format) and give a name with any extension</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">2.</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">=&gt; </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">crontab</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> &lt;your file name&gt;</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">3.</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">Note: This will remove your old entries in the cron entries.</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">Troubleshooting:</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">If your cron is doing nothing means you have a problem with your PATH.</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">⁃</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">Make sure that the cron know about your program and whatever you execute in your program.</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">⁃</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">    ( you might call other programs and the cron wants to know where are they)</span></div><div><br/></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">If your &quot;date&quot; command is not working, you might be using the $(date …) command which</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">some cron ( like in RedHat) does not like &quot;$(…)&quot; construction. So, try to replace with</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">the backslash (The </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">backslash</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;"> key is located near the &quot;Enter&quot; or &quot;Return&quot; key on most </span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica; font-weight: bold;">keyboards)</span></div><div><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">⁃</span><span style="font: 17.0px Helvetica;">Also, make sure that the cron finds the &quot;date&quot; command ( i.e. /bin/date)</span></div><div><br/></div></en-note>
